MissionCommands.Message: Good morning {{profileName}}. Today you will learn how to perform the Deorbit, Entry, and Landing procedures.
The Gemini spacecraft is designed to allow for a controlled atmospheric entry, descent and landing on Earth.
Atmospheric drag and aerodynamic heating can cause a spacecraft to break up and disintegrate completely, which is why mastering this procedure is critical.
Before the spacecraft can land it needs to perform a deorbit burn. This is the retrograde burn that will take the trajectory of the craft through the atmosphere.
Just before re-entry, both the adapter and the retrograde section are jettisoned. Once the retrograde section separates, the spacecraft's heat shield is exposed.

The tip/nose of the capsule contains a parachute system. During the landing phase, small explosives will deploy the parachutes to slow the capsule's descent. The capsule will shortly after make a big splash in the ocean and float until a rescue ship retrieves the vehicle and astronauts.
Let's get started. We are currently ~80 minutes from the start of the re-entry.

During these procedures you might notice the use of C/Bs. These refer to circuit breaker switches used to power various systems, and look like normal switches located on the left/right and overhead panels.
We need to maneuver the spacecraft to its retrograde attitude. In the PROP MOTOR VALVES section, set OAMS to OPEN.
In the CNTL PWR section, switch OAMS to ON.

The OAMS is needed to be able to maneuver the craft. It is important to always pay attention to the attitude of the craft before the retrograde burn to ensure the engines are pointing in the correct direction.
Verify ATTITUDE CONTROL is set to PLAT.
This will hold the attitude to the selected PLATFORM.
Then, set the PLATFORM to BEF.
The spacecraft should now be maneuvering towards the retrograde attitude. When the maneuver is complete, use RATE COMMAND or DIRECT to manually adjust ROLL to zero. Press ROGER when done.
Set the Computer Mode to PRE LN.
Then press START on the computer. The computer should now be running the PRE LN program.
The Time to Retro (Tr) decide when the retrograde sequence and engines should ignite. This can be checked on the OBC.
Press [1] on the MDIU.
Next press [9] on the MDIU.
And finally press [READ OUT].
The new reading will show time for Retro burn in minutes:seconds, where the message is formatted as MMM:SS. We have about one orbit to prepare for entry, much more than really needed.
One important tool during entry is the Event Timer, so let us start by learning how to use it. Set the Event Timer mode to STOP.
Then open [C] MISSION TOOLS -> COCKPIT FUNCTIONS -> RESET EVENT TIMER. This will set the Event Timer to 00:00. Press ROGER when done.
We will set the Event Timer to a count down from 20:00 minutes. Turn the Event Timer Dial counterclockwise (Left) to increase numbers until getting to 20:00 minutes.
Once 20:00 is displayed, turn dial clockwise back to middle position. Note: The other positions are used to increase/decrease seconds.
And finally, set the Event Timer count direction to DOWN.
Let us get familiar with the entry procedures. Open the checklists from the MISSION PAD. Two sections are relevant for deorbit, entry and landing. Find the ENTRY and the LANDING sections.
These sections contains all the checklists we will be using today. Read through them and try to get a good overview of the procedures and what to expect, it will be time well invested.
Switch to PULSE, RATE COMMAND, or DIRECT, and manually align the spacecraft to zero roll, ensuring the Earth is positioned below you (heads-up). Press ROGER when complete.
Let us refresh the Time to Retro on the OBC. Press [READ OUT] on the MDIU.

The time to retro (Tr) will show each time you press READ OUT on CORE 19 since the computer is running. If the computer would be loading a module for example, it would not be possible to read this value.
The first part of the ENTRY section is the PRE RETRO checklist. This checklist will prepare us for the retrograde burn.

We have already set up the Event Timer, but it is important that you correctly set up the event timer when instructed as CORE 19 will be unavailable while the OBC loads the entry module. RUN the checklist now.
Proceed with the checklist until it asks you to start the Event Timer at Tr -20:00 minutes (CORE 19 02000). When you see this step, press ROGER.

You will need to press READ OUT multiple times on CORE 19. Your job is to then start the Event Timer when CORE 19 reaches 02000 (020:00 minutes). Follow the checklist and press ROGER when the T -20:00 minutes countdown has started (feel free to carefully use time scale).

Complete the checklist. This will first set the OBC module to REENT, then wait for the module to load. Recall that the green tape light (RUN) indicates that the tape is running, meaning the module is loading. When the light goes out, the loading is complete and you can complete the checklist.
The REENT module should now be running and we should be about 10 minutes away from the planned ignition. Press READ OUT to get the exat time to retro and crosscheck with the Event Timer.
If you are not yet familiar with the steps ahead, spend a minute getting familiar with the 256 SEC TO RETRO and 1 MIN TO RETRO checklists.
The next checklist we will run is the 256 SEC TO RETRO (4 minutes, 16 seconds). We will use the RUN feature to do this. Do this now.

The first thing it asks you to do is to wait for the Event Timer to reach T -4:16 min, 256 seconds before the burn. This checklist will verify critical switch configurations. Proceed when at T -4:16min.

Complete the checklist. At the end of this checklist, it will ask you to perform the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist. This will be where all the sequencer buttons will be pressed. It will be a lot in short time, so be prepared.
RUN the 1 MIN TO RETRO checklist.
Maintain requested attitude while waiting for the Event Timer to reach T -1min and then complete the checklist following the steps and timing precisely.
Retros should has been fired and the retrograde section staged. RUN the POST RETRO JETTISON checklist.
When the retrograde engines fired, the dV was counting up on the IVIs as the burn progressed and is now visible on the IVIs. Complete the checklist.

Use RATE COMMAND (RE-ENT) to maneuver the craft to 180 in roll, 20 pitch down, and 0 yaw. In this attitude, the Earth Horizon should be in your upper window, and your head is pointing down towards Earth.
Let's talk about maneuvering in the atmosphere. You need to monitor your LONG-ACCEL gauge. Be careful to not build up too much G-forces. Never exceed 10 G's.

To control G-forces, you will be using ROLL. Maintain attitude in pitch and yaw by zeroing the error needles while you are in the upper parts of the atmosphere. Once drag is detected, air density will automatically move the spacecraft into a stable atmospheric attitude. Let us go through some of the theory.
The capsule is designed to generate lift. When your heads are pointing down towards Earth, the lift vector points up.
When your heads are pointing up, the lift vector points down towards Earth.
When you reach 400K' ft altitude, roll the spacecraft to heads down, so the lift vector points up. We should already be in this attitude now.
When 0.05G is detected, the IVIs will show the range to the touchdown point and will start to count down.

When this happens roll so the spacecraft is in a heads up position, diving down into the atmosphere. Pay attention to the G-forces, and when it exceeds 3G's, reverse the roll so the lift vector points up/heads down again.
The longer you keep the lift vector up, the longer the capsule will travel before splashing down.
Ok, let us perform the entry. Ensure you have the horizon in the upper window (upside down) and wait for 0.05G. The cue for this is that the IVIs starts to count.
When the IVIs start to count down, roll to 0 degrees and maintain roll.
During reentry, your spacecraft will shake as it gets struck by the atmosphere, burning depicted as a bright yellow light wrapping around the capsule.

Continue to wait for 3Gs before the reverse roll. After that, maneuver to maintain G-forces below 10 G's. Recall if you are heads down, the lift vector points upwards and you will reduce G-loads. If you are heads up, the lift vector points downwards, and your G-loads will increase.
Well done. Quickly, RUN the Landing checklist and follow it during the descent.
Take a look at the [40K] and [10.6K] indicators.
When [40K] indicator lights up, press the HI ALT DROGUE button. This will Deploy the Altitude Drogue.
When [10.6K] indicator lights up, press the PARA button. This will Deploy the Parachute.
The Landing attitude can be set after main chute deploy. Press LDG ATT to tilt the capsule to its splash down attitude.
Prepare for splashdown.
Congratulations, you just landed safely!
The final checklist to run is the POST LANDING checklist. RUN this now.
This will release the chute and power down things not needed after splashdown.
Congratulations, this completes the deorbit, entry and landing lesson. It has been a long lesson but an important one. Feel free to re-run if things are unclear.

Title: Tutorial 8 - Deorbit, Entry & Landing
Description: In this lesson we will learn how to perform the Deorbit-Reentry-Landing procedure which is a requirement for every Gemini Program mission.
BriefingText: On early Gemini flights, astronauts manually controlled much of the spacecraft's maneuvers during re-entry. Just before re-entry, the Gemini capsule would jettison the retrograde section, leaving only the cone-shaped spacecraft holding the crew. In most cases, the astronauts used the capsule's controls to maneuver it so that the large, blunt end faced the Earth. The friction generated from the spacecraft moving through the atmosphere at tremendous speeds produced intense heat. Without the heat shield on the base of the Gemini spacecraft, the astronauts inside the capsule wouldn't have been able to survive. Finally the Gemini Spacecraft lands safely in the Atlantic Ocean.
